        <!-- Quick Answer -->
        <div class="lj-quick-answer">
          <p>Rose gold engagement rings use a gold alloy blended with copper to produce the characteristic warm pink tone. The copper content determines the depth of the pink colour - more copper means deeper rose, less means a lighter, more golden pink. In Canada in 2026, rose gold remains one of the top metal choices for engagement rings, particularly with oval, pear, and vintage-inspired settings. I'm Suman Smith, founder of Lux Jewels. I've been designing rose gold lab-grown engagement rings across Canada since 2007. In 2015, I became the first Canadian jeweller to specialize exclusively in lab-grown stones.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Main prose -->
        <div class="lj-prose">

          <p>I don't treat rose gold as just a colour option. The warm tone of rose gold interacts with stone colour grades in specific ways - it can enhance the warmth of G-H colour stones or create a beautiful contrast with colourless D-F diamonds. Choosing the right stone grade for a rose gold setting is part of the design process.</p>

          <p>
            <a href="https://luxjewels.com/booking-appointment/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Book a free video consultation</a> |
            <a href="/lab-grown-engagement-rings/">Browse the full collection</a>
          </p>

          <h2>What Is Rose Gold and How Is It Made?</h2>

          <p>Pure gold (24K) is too soft for jewellery. Engagement ring settings are made from gold alloys - mixtures of gold with other metals that add hardness. The alloy composition determines both the gold purity designation (14K, 18K) and the colour.</p>

          <p><strong>Rose gold = gold + copper + sometimes silver</strong></p>

          <p>The copper content creates the pink tint:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>More copper = deeper, warmer rose/pink</li>
            <li>Less copper = lighter, more champagne gold tone</li>
            <li>Some rose gold alloys also include small amounts of silver to lighten and balance the colour</li>
          </ul>

          <p><strong>14K vs 18K Rose Gold:</strong></p>

          <div class="lj-table-wrap">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Feature</th>
                  <th>14K Rose Gold</th>
                  <th>18K Rose Gold</th>
                </tr>
